{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623260"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:09:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:09:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16839"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16839"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.38,0,0.48,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9529"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67224"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9529"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52676"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5060"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22508"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22510"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67224"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman develops hypotension following general anaesthesia. The anaesthetist administers metaraminol to increase her blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of metaraminol?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Selective noradrenaline reuptake inhibitor","Pure alpha-1 receptor agonist","Pure alpha-2 receptor agonist","Mixed alpha-1 agonist and noradrenaline releasing agent","Pure beta-1 receptor agonist"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMetaraminol works through two main mechanisms. It is a \u003Cstrong\u003Emixed alpha-1 agonist and noradrenaline releasing agent\u003C/strong\u003E, causing vasoconstriction both directly through alpha-1 receptor stimulation and indirectly by promoting noradrenaline release from sympathetic nerve terminals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other, incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective noradrenaline reuptake inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E: this mechanism would be too slow for acute blood pressure control; metaraminol works by releasing noradrenaline rather than preventing reuptake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPure alpha-1 receptor agonist\u003C/strong\u003E: while metaraminol does have direct alpha-1 effects, it also has significant indirect sympathomimetic effects through noradrenaline release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPure alpha-2 receptor agonist\u003C/strong\u003E: metaraminol primarily acts on alpha-1 receptors to cause vasoconstriction, not alpha-2 receptors which would have different clinical effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPure beta-1 receptor agonist\u003C/strong\u003E: metaraminol has minimal beta receptor activity and primarily works through alpha-1 mediated vasoconstriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combined direct and indirect sympathomimetic effects make metaraminol an effective vasopressor for treating hypotension. Its predominant alpha-1 effects result in peripheral vasoconstriction and increased blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metaraminol is a sympathomimetic drug that acts as both a direct alpha-1 agonist and indirect sympathomimetic by releasing noradrenaline.","The primary clinical effect of metaraminol is vasoconstriction leading to increased blood pressure.","Metaraminol has minimal beta receptor activity compared to other sympathomimetics."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52676"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16839"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52676"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T08:51:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T08:52:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9529"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67224"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attribu